h2. Caching parsing data

Most state displayed in the studio left and right hand side panels originates from code analysis - parsing source code to retrieve data.

Selecting different elements in the Canvas screen triggers new code analysis to fetch the necessary data and then displays it.

The codegen backend could benefit from caching the results of the code analysis so that we didn't have to traverse/analyse the source code as much. For the implementation itself we can start by moving the most frequent visitors to our {{sync}} process and cache the visitors result. 

When it comes to cache invalidation a naive approach could be re-parsing everything on each sync (sync currently works like that where it applies the same transformations every time - i.e. inline styles might not have been added but it still tries to extract them).

A better approach for cache invalidation is to introduce granularity. Only parse AST nodes that changed and its respective branch. I.e: a codegen action added an import at the top level of the module, we only need to re-parse this node within the Program node body, not all body nodes. Flagging codegen actions that only do code analysis could also help so that those are ignored in the cache invalidation process. No need to re-parse an AST that didn't change.

h2. Examples of repeat parsing operations that could benefit from cache

Parsing imports info - retrieves "local", "imported" and "source" values for all imports in the current file. 

