column33:
*Current Implementation*
The current implementation sees the need to import the eventBus interface in every component where we need to either trigger a new Event or listen to registered events between components. I addition to this, extra implementation is needed to close opened event listeners (which in some cases are left open)

*Solution*

The implementation implements an auto register of events when a component is created and also closes listeners to created events when a component is destroyed. The benefits with this include;

* We don’t need to import the eventBus anywhere since it is registered when Vue app is created
* We do not need to add extra code to close registered events since this is done behind the hood when a component is destroyed

*Usage*

*Triggering an event*

To use the new implementation; we need to call {{this.$eventBus.$emit('event-name', payload)}} to trigger an event.
Please note that the payload is optional incase you don’t need to pass data between components with the eventBus. Hence, in this case, you would trigger an event in this way; {{this.$eventBus.$emit('event-name')}} 

Example

{code:javascript} // Inline example
 <button @click="$eventBus.$emit('show-alert')">Test</button>`

export default {
  methods: {
    testEventBus() {
      this.$eventBus.$emit('show-alert', 'some data')
    }
  }
}{code}

*Listening to events*

To listen to events triggered is the easiest. You will just need to declared the events you want to listen to inside a specific component inside the {{eventBusCallbacks}} hook I added to the options API. It uses a key value pair where the left hand side is the event name and the right is the component local method name that will be triggered.

Example

{code:javascript}export default {
  eventBusCallbacks: {
    'show-alert': 'showAlertTriggeredByEventBus',
  },
  methods: {
    showAlertTriggeredByEventBus(payload) {
      console.log('Event triggered..', payload)
    }
  }
}{code}



